Title : Beaver Harbour (British Columbia)
Text : {{distinguish|Beaver Cove (British Columbia)}}
'''Beaver Harbour''' is a [[harbour]] or [[bay]] on northern [[Vancouver Island]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]], located to the east of the town of [[Port Hardy]].<ref>[http://apps.gov.bc.ca/pub/bcgnws/names/22712.html BC Names/GeoBC entry "Beaver Harbour (bay)"]</ref>  '''Beaver Harbour Provincial Park''' was located on the west side of the bay but was transferred to local governance in 1970.<ref>[http://apps.gov.bc.ca/pub/bcgnws/names/51214.html BC Names/GeoBC entry "Beaver Harbour Park"]</ref>

==History and name origin==
Spanish commanders [[Dionisio Alcalá Galiano|Galiano]] and [[Antonio Valdés y Fernández Bazán|Valdez]] conferred the name '''Puerto de Guemes''' after the Viceroy of Mexico.  The harbour was labelled "Daedalus Harbour" on an 1850 sketch by a Mr. Dillon of the [[Royal Navy]], after {{HMS|Daedalus|1826|6}}; the name "Beaver Harbour" first appeared on Lieutenant Mansell's 1851 plan of the harbour.<ref>''British Columbia Coast Names, 1592-1906: their origin and history'', Capt. J.T. Walbran, Ottawa, 1909, quote in the BC Names/GeoBC entry</ref>

Beaver Harbour, like [[Beaver Cove (British Columbia)|Beaver Cove]], was named for {{ship||Beaver|steamship|2}}, the first steam vessel on the Pacific Northwest Coast, which was in service to the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] for many decades until wrecked at [[Prospect Point (British Columbia)|Prospect Point]] in [[Stanley Park]], [[Vancouver]], in 1888.<ref>[http://apps.gov.bc.ca/pub/bcgnws/names/22712.html BC Names/GeoBC entry "Beaver Harbour (bay)"]</ref>

